## Bug 4: `emit_li32` Generates Wrong Code for High-Half-Only Values

```cpp
static int emit_li32(uint32_t* out, uint8_t rt, uint32_t imm) {
    uint16_t lo = (uint16_t)(imm & 0xFFFF);
    uint16_t hi = (uint16_t)(imm >> 16);
    if (hi == 0) {
        out[0] = ppc_addi(rt, 0, (int16_t)lo);   // ← if lo >= 0x8000, sign-extends!
        return 1;
    } else if (lo == 0) {
        out[0] = ppc_addis(rt, 0, (int16_t)hi);
        return 1;
    } else {
        out[0] = ppc_addis(rt, 0, (int16_t)hi);  // ← if lo >= 0x8000, addis loads hi+1!
        out[1] = ppc_ori(rt, rt, lo);
        return 2;
    }
}
```

`addis` then `ori` is correct only if you account for `ori`'s zero-extension. But `addi` sign-extends, so loading e.g. `0x0000E3xx` (your crash address!) with `addi r3, 0, 0xE3xx` produces `0xFFFFE3xx`. **This is why you get reads from `0x000000e3`** — a truncated/corrupted address.

**Fix:**

```cpp
static int emit_li32(uint32_t* out, uint8_t rt, uint32_t imm) {
    uint16_t lo = (uint16_t)(imm & 0xFFFF);
    uint16_t hi = (uint16_t)(imm >> 16);

    if (imm == 0) {
        out[0] = ppc_addi(rt, 0, 0);   // li rt, 0
        return 1;
    }

    // If lo has bit15 set, addis must load hi+1 to compensate for
    // addi's sign extension — but we use ori (zero-extend), so
    // we only need addis when hi != 0.
    if (hi == 0) {
        // lo fits in 16 bits unsigned; use ori r0,r0 then ori
        // Actually: addi r,0,lo sign-extends — WRONG for lo >= 0x8000
        // Use: addis rt,0,0 then ori rt,rt,lo
        out[0] = ppc_addi(rt, 0, 0);
        out[1] = ppc_ori(rt, rt, lo);
        return (lo == 0) ? 1 : 2;
    } else if (lo == 0) {
        out[0] = ppc_addis(rt, 0, (int16_t)hi);
        return 1;
    } else {
        out[0] = ppc_addis(rt, 0, (int16_t)hi);
        out[1] = ppc_ori(rt, rt, lo);
        return 2;
    }
}
```

